5. Execution Flow

Step-by-step

1. Input arrives

User → Normalizer → Canonical Object

2. CCL publishes

publish(object)

3. Router subscribes + decides modules

4. Selected modules execute

Each returns raw output

⸻

5. Translation

raw_output → Translation Engine → canonical objects


⸻

6. Re-publish

All outputs go back into CCL

⸻

7. Combination (Pantheon Nucleus)

Consumes canonical objects

⸻

8. Conflict check

CCL intercepts contradictions

⸻

9. Final synthesis

Returned through CCL → Output

⸻

6. APIs (Minimal Spec)

Publish

def publish(object: CanonicalObject) -> None

Subscribe

def subscribe(module_id: str, filter_fn) -> Stream

Query State

def query(filters: dict) -> List[CanonicalObject]

Trace

def trace(object_id: str) -> ProvenanceChain

Resolve Conflict

def resolve(conflict_set: List[CanonicalObject]) -> Resolution


⸻

7. Module Contracts (Critical)

Every connected module must implement:

class Module:
    def input_schema(self) -> Schema
    def output_schema(self) -> Schema
    def execute(self, input_objects) -> raw_output
    def adapter(self) -> TranslationAdapter


⸻

8. Constraints (Hard Rules)

8.1 No Direct Module-to-Module Calls

Everything flows through CCL.

8.2 All Outputs Must Be Canonicalized

No raw outputs past CCL boundary.

8.3 Provenance Is Mandatory

No anonymous data allowed.

8.4 Confidence Required

Every object must include uncertainty.

8.5 Reversibility

State snapshots must be restorable.

⸻

9. Failure Modes + Mitigations

A. Semantic Drift

→ fix with strict schema + validation

B. Overhead / Latency

→ batching + async pub/sub

C. Conflict Explosion

→ threshold gating before escalation

D. Garbage Memory

→ periodic pruning + weighting

